{{Infobox ecoregion | name = Baffin coastal tundra | image = Baffin_Island_Northeast_Coast_1997-08-07.jpg | image_caption = [[Sam Ford Fjord]] shoreline on the eastern side of the [[Remote Peninsula]] | image_size = 300 | country = [[Canada]] | state = | country1 = | rivers = | elevation = | bird_species = [[Snow bunting]] | mammal_species = [[Polar bear]], [[Arctic hare]], [[Arctic fox]], [[lemming]], [[caribou]] | habitat_loss = 0 | habitat_loss_ref = | protected = 0 | protected_ref = | area = 9100 | geology = rocky coast, fjords | biome = [[Tundra]] | animals = | map = Baffin coastal tundra map.svg | map_caption = 1105. Baffin Coastal Tundra | map_size = 248 }}
The '''Baffin coastal tundra''' is a small [[ecoregion]] of the far north of North America, on the central north coast of [[Baffin Island]] in the [[Canada|Canadian]] territory of [[Nunavut]]. This is permafrost tundra with an average annual temperature below freezing.
==Setting== This ecoregion is a small stretch of coastal plain on the north coast of Baffin Island. The coast is rocky with many [[fjord]]s carved by glaciers into the [[Baffin Mountains]]. The cold Arctic climate consists of a short summers (mean temperature 1°C) and a long, cold winter (mean temperature -22.5°C).<ref>{{WWF ecoregion|id=na1105|name=Baffin coastal tundra}}</ref>
==Flora== The plant cover is sparse in the drier areas while the wetter areas have a fair cover of mosses, [[sedge]]s, shrubs such as [[purple saxifrage]], [[Arctic willow]], and [[Papaver radicatum|Arctic poppy]] and rushes.
==Fauna== This coast is a breeding area for the [[snow bunting]] and is home to [[polar bear]], [[Arctic hare]], [[Arctic fox]], [[lemming]], and [[caribou]].
==Threats and preservation== This ecoregion is almost intact although there are no protected areas.
