{{More citations needed|date={{currentmonthname}} {{currentyear}}}}
This is a list of notable [[microburst]]s.
== List == * July 13, 1890 – A microburst capsized the vessel ''[[Sea Wing disaster|Sea Wing]]'' on [[Lake Pepin]] between Wisconsin and Minnesota, killing 98 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/july-14-1890-sea-wing-capsizes-on-lake-pepin/284253911/|title=July 14, 1890: Sea Wing capsizes on Lake Pepin|publisher=}}</ref> * A particularly violent microburst is a possible alternative explanation to the 1961 sinking of the American school brigantine ''[[Albatross (1920 schooner)|Albatross]]''. The ship's captain Dr. [[Christopher Sheldon]] claimed that the ship was hit by a [[white squall]] on the voyage from [[Progreso, Yucatán]], to [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]] in the [[Bahamas]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}} * 1980–1995 – [[Federal Aviation Administration|FAA]]-supported investigations into microburst morphology and microburst detection and warning systems. Principals: [[Ted Fujita]], [[University of Chicago|U. Chicago]], John McCarthy and James Wilson, [[National Center for Atmospheric Research|NCAR]], J. Evans and Marilyn M. Wolfson, MIT [[Lincoln Laboratory]], R Bowles and F Proctor, [[National Aeronautic and Space Administration|NASA]]). Hundreds of microbursts were detected and studied, many by dual [[Weather radar#Velocity|Doppler weather radar]] analysis. Several had intensities in excess of {{convert|80|kn|mi/h km/h|lk=on}}.<ref>1982 John McCarthy, James Wilson, T. Theodore Fujita. The Joint Airport Weather Studies Project, Bull. AMS 83.</ref><ref>1989 Kimberly L. Elmore and John McCarthy, A Statistical Characterization of Denver-Area Microbursts, DOT/FAA/NR-92/13</ref><ref>1994 Marilyn M. Wolfson, et al, Characteristics of Microbursts in the Continental United States, Lincoln Laboratory Journal Volume 1, Number 11</ref> * August 1, 1983 – The strongest microburst recorded at an airport was observed at [[Andrews Air Force Base]], Maryland, near Washington, DC. The wind speeds may have exceeded {{convert|150|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} in this microburst. The peak gust was recorded at 2:11 PM –-7 minutes after [[Air Force One]], with the President on board, landed on the same runway.<ref>Fujita, T. T., 1984. Andrews AFB microburst on 01 August 1983. The impact of weather on aviation safety. Hearings before the subcommittee on investigations and oversight, 97th Congress, 1st Session and 98th Congress, 1st Session: U.S. Government Printing Office, p. 475-477.</ref> * May 1986 – A microburst [[squall]] with windspeeds of {{convert|80|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} is responsible for capsizing and sinking the ''[[Pride of Baltimore]]'' in the [[Caribbean Sea]], about {{convert|250|mi|km|abbr=on}} north of [[Puerto Rico]]. The ship took the lives of her captain and three of her other 11 crew members.<ref>http://www.pride2.org/history/ogp.php</ref> * July 8, 1989 – [[Denver]] [[Stapleton International Airport]]. After being alerted by [[Low level windshear alert system|LLWAS]] of an imminent encounter with a {{convert|95|kn|mi/h km/h|abbr=on}} microburst, Captain Craig Levine initiated a missed approach, taking his [[Boeing 737]] to full takeoff power, climbing {{convert|400|ft|m|abbr=on}} and adding {{convert|40|kn|mi/h km/h|abbr=on}} of airspeed. Encountering the microburst at full takeoff power, they lost {{convert|400|ft|m|abbr=on}} of altitude and lost {{convert|50|kn|mi/h km/h|abbr=on}} of airspeed in about one-half of a minute. This event is a documented "save" of an airplane by a windshear alert system.<ref>Case Study. http://llwas-technology.com/corp/case-study/</ref><ref>1990 F. Wesley Wilson, et al, An Intense Microburst at Denver's Stapleton International Airport. Proceedings of the Air Traffic Assoc., Boston</ref><ref>1990 D. Hughs, LLWAS credited with helping 737 survive major microburst. Aviation Week & Space Technology;7/16/90, Vol. 133 Issue 3, p91</ref><ref>1993 F. H. Proctor, Case Study of a Low-Reflectivity Pulsating Microburst: Numerical Simulation of the Denver, 8 July 1989, Storm. 7th Conference on Severe Local Storms, St. Louis, Missouri. American Meteorological Society</ref> * August 7, 1994 – Severe thunderstorms produce numerous reports of damaging winds (and large hail) across central, southern, and southeastern Oklahoma. The worst damage occurs in [[Prague, Oklahoma|Prague]], where estimated winds of {{convert|90|mph|abbr=on}} produced widespread damage across town, downed the steeple of a church, partially unroofed the [[Prague High School (Oklahoma)|high school]], and damaged to destroyed mobile homes.<ref name="SD9408"/> * August 17, 1994 – A series of extreme [[downburst]]s are produced by a southward moving long-lived supercell thunderstorm across south-central Kansas and western Oklahoma, whereafter new severe storms fire in western Oklahoma and drop into north Texas. Severe damage occurs across a long and narrow swath with numerous reports of {{convert|80|-|100|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} winds and a then record gust of {{convert|113|mph|abbr=on}} is measured at the [[Lahoma, Oklahoma|Lahoma]] [[Oklahoma Mesonet]] site. At least two tornadoes and windblown hail the size of [[softball]]s and [[Football (ball)#American and Canadian football|footballs]] also occur.<ref>{{cite book |title=Weathering the Storm: Tornadoes, Television, and Turmoil |last=England |first=Gary |year=1996 |publisher=University of Oklahoma Press |location=Norman, Oklahoma |isbn=0-8061-2823-2 |pages= 198–201}}</ref><ref name="SD9408">{{cite web|url=http://www1.ncdc.noaa.gov/pub/orders/IPS/IPS-E1D3C74B-E78A-4119-AED1-B0ACBC06280F.pdf|title=''Storm Data'', August 1994|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://okfirst.mesonet.org/train/casestudies/17aug94/17aug94.html|title=OK-FIRST Case Study: The Lahoma, Oklahoma Storm of August 17, 1994|first=Stdrovia|last=Blackburn|website=okfirst.mesonet.org}}</ref> * July 15, 1995 – A series of microbursts hit northern and eastern [[New York (state)|New York State]], killing 5 people, injuring 11, and causing nearly a half billion dollars in damages. It was the second [[derecho]] of a [[Heat wave of 1995 derecho series|series]] during mid-July. The storms severely damaged {{convert|125,000|acre|ha sqmi sqkm|lk=on}} of forest in the [[Adirondack Park]], necessitating the helicopter rescue of 31 hikers/backpackers stranded in the backcountry due to blocked trails.<ref>http://www.erh.noaa.gov/aly/Past/derecho95/derecho.html</ref> * May 21, 1996 – A microburst caused extensive damage and 60 injuries in [[Plymouth County, Massachusetts]], where winds were clocked at {{convert|104|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}}. Brockton, Whitman, and Abington were the hardest hit towns.{{Citation needed|date=April 2014}} * On August 14, 1996 a [[severe thunderstorm]] and its accompanying [[dry microburst]] hit the northwest portion of the [[Phoenix metropolitan area]], ripping off tile roofs and causing $160 million in damage. An [[Arizona]]-record wind gust of {{convert|115|mph|abbr=on}} was recorded at the [[Phoenix Deer Valley Airport|Deer Valley Airport]]. A few locations had to go without power for several days.<ref>http://www.wrh.noaa.gov/psr/general/history/index.php?wfo=psr&page=top</ref> * In the early hours of September 7, 1998, a microburst hit the city of [[Syracuse, New York]]. Three people were killed and the area suffered $130 million in damages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/misc/AbtDerechos/casepages/sep71998page.htm|title=The Labor Day Derechos of 1998|website=www.spc.noaa.gov}}</ref> * On March 12, 2006, at approximately 8:10 AM, a severe microburst with winds varying from {{convert|70|-|90|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} damaged large portions of [[Lawrence, Kansas]]. Reported damage included downed power lines, stop lights and trees, overturned semi-trailers, collapsed farm silos and damage to roofs. Seventy buildings on the [[University of Kansas]] campus reported damage. In total, over $8 million in damages was estimated.<ref>[http://www.crh.noaa.gov/images/top/2007KANSAS.pdf National Weather Service 2006 Report], ''National Weather Service Institute''.</ref> * On May 6, 2008, a microburst made by a LP/HP [[supercell]] hit [[Olton, Texas]]. It did no damage. * On November 16, 2008, a microburst during a severe supercell thunderstorm unleashed major havoc on the suburb of [[The Gap, Queensland|The Gap]] in [[Brisbane]], Queensland, Australia.<ref>[http://www.bom.gov.au/qld/cyclone/thunderstorms/16Nov2008/qldth20081116.shtml SEQ Severe Thunderstorm and Microburst at The Gap], ''Bureau of Meteorology - Australian Government''.</ref> * On February 12, 2009, high winds from a microburst caused a {{convert|92|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} wind gust in [[West Mifflin, Pennsylvania]]. Several damages were reported including roofs and garages collapsing.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}} * On May 2, 2009, a microburst struck the [[Dallas Cowboys]] indoor practice facility in [[Irving, Texas]], causing the roof to collapse. 12 people were hospitalized.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=4127852 "Injuries reported at Cowboys' facility"] ESPN.com, 3 May 2009. Retrieved 21 July 2009.</ref> * On July 11, 2009, winds believed to be caused by a microburst uprooted trees and brought down close to 30 [[utility pole]]s in [[Mississauga]], Ontario.<ref>[http://www.680news.com/news/headlines/more.jsp?content=20090712_010506_1464], ''680 News''.</ref><ref>[https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/664626], ''Toronto Star''.</ref> * On July 21, 2009, a strong thunderstorm produced a probable microburst in the western and southern suburbs of Denver, Colorado, causing extensive damage to trees and property. Cities that were most affected were [[Lakewood, Colorado|Lakewood]], [[Wheat Ridge, Colorado|Wheat Ridge]], and [[Arvada, Colorado|Arvada]].<ref>[http://cbs4denver.com/weatherupdates/weather.denver.colorado.2.1094115.html "Storms Knock Out Power, Uproot Trees In Denver"] KCNC.com, 21 July 2009. Retrieved 21 July 2009.</ref> * In the evening of August 18, 2009, an isolated thunderstorm originated in [[Bridgewater Township, New Jersey|Bridgewater]] when a boundary generated from rain-cooled air associated with the isolated thunderstorm quickly shifted east toward [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]], New Jersey. Shortly thereafter, the isolated thunderstorm quickly intensified strong-to-severe while in the vicinity of Newark and after the intensification, the isolated severe thunderstorm produced {{convert|0.75|in|cm|abbr=on}} [[hail]] in [[Hoboken, New Jersey|Hoboken]] and [[Weehawken, New Jersey|Weehawken]]. The isolated severe thunderstorm changed direction from moving east to northeast as the thunderstorm approached and shortly affected [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]]. The isolated severe thunderstorm was responsible for producing {{convert|70|kn|mi/h km/h|abbr=on}} thunderstorm wind gust, resulted a possible microburst that downed over few more than 500 trees, damaged several automobiles and spread debris across some streets.<ref>[http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/08/19/storm-topples-scores-of-trees-in-central-park/?em "Storm Toppled Scores of Trees in Central Park"] nytimes.com, 19 August 2009.</ref> * On February 17, 2010, a microburst caused the capsizing and sinking of the [[tall ship]] ''[[Concordia (ship)|Concordia]]'' some {{convert|550|km|mi|abbr=on}} southeast of [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]] in rough seas.<ref name=CBC>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/world/story/2010/02/19/ns-brazil-ship-sinks-students.html |title=Students safe after capsizing of N.S.-based ship |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=21 February 2010 | date=February 19, 2010}}</ref> All 64 people who were on board (48 students attending school on board, eight teachers and eight crew) were rescued from 5 life rafts by merchant vessels. * In the afternoon of June 24, 2010, there were reports of {{convert|52|kn|mi/h km/h|abbr=on}} thunderstorm winds that downed tree limbs with some roads temporarily blocked by fallen tree limbs as the linear cluster of severe thunderstorms impacted across northern New Jersey and southeastern [[New York (state)|New York]]. [[Nutley, New Jersey|Nutley]], [[Cliffside Park, New Jersey|Cliffside Park]], and [[Pompton Lakes, New Jersey|Pompton]] are locations that reported downed tree limbs. {{convert|61|kn|mi/h km/h|abbr=on}} thunderstorm wind was reported in [[State University of New York Maritime College|SUNY Maritime College]] that knocked down trees and tree limbs when the linear clusters quickly changed into a severe thunderstorm after leaving [[The Bronx]] and central portions of Manhattan counties. {{convert|54|kn|mi/h km/h|abbr=on}} thunderstorm gust was reported twice in [[LaGuardia Airport]] and fallen trees destroyed two homes and one car in [[College Point, Queens|College Point]]. {{convert|70|kn|mi/h km/h|abbr=on}} thunderstorm wind was reported in [[Whitestone, Queens|Whitestone]], responsible for downed numerous utility poles, street lamps, trees, at least one collapsed chimney, and damaged several vehicles, including a destroyed mini-van. Besides from thunderstorm wind damage, a [[funnel cloud]] was reported over [[Flushing Bay]] and the severe thunderstorm dumped at least golf ball sized hail in [[Queens]] side of [[Throgs Neck Bridge]] that was reported earlier with at least one car dented. After the aftermath of northeastern Queens, the severe thunderstorm produced {{convert|64|kn|mi/h km/h|abbr=on}} thunderstorm gust in [[Kings Point, New York|Kings Point]] and {{convert|87|kn|mi/h km/h|abbr=on}} thunderstorm wind that was reported near [[Great Neck, New York|Great Neck]], resulted a microburst that accompanied dime-to-quarter sized hail and downed numerous large trees, powerlines and uprooted trees. The microburst produced winds exceeding {{convert|60|-|100|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} that caused significant damage to homes and automobiles across [[Long Island]].<ref>[http://www.longislandpress.com/2010/06/24/severe-winds-knock-out-power-delay-trains/] Long Island Press, retrieved 25 June 2010.</ref> * In the afternoon of June 24, 2010, a severe thunderstorm resembling characteristics of a [[supercell]] produced a [[wet microburst]] exceed {{convert|100|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} winds and severe hail in the townships of [[Drexel Hill, Pennsylvania|Drexel Hill]], [[Springfield Township, Delaware County, Pennsylvania|Springfield]], and [[Broomall, Pennsylvania|Broomall]], Pennsylvania in [[Delaware County, Pennsylvania|Delaware County]], uprooted trees and damaged homes.<ref>http://www.erh.noaa.gov/phi/storms/06262010.html</ref> * On August 25, 2010, a microburst storm squall hit in the [[Lake Elsinore, California]] had snapped power poles. * On September 1, 2010, a microburst was reported in [[West Yellowstone, Montana]]. The microburst, originally thought to be a [[tornado]], topped at {{convert|80|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}}, and ripped off 90% of the roof at Yellowstone Park Inn and Suites.<ref>[http://www.westyellowstonenews.com/news/article_23cad3f9-d6ff-5673-8af5-276f89b7cb03.html Microburst tears path of destruction through West Yellowstone], West Yellowstone News. Retrieved 12 May 2011.</ref> * On September 16, 2010, a [[macroburst]] was reported in the [[Middle Village, Queens|Middle Village]] and [[Forest Hills, Queens|Forest Hills]] areas of Queens, New York during an unexpected linear/[[Bow echo|bowing]] segments contained intense thunderstorms that spawned two weak tornadoes. In a city with a population of 9 million people,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/popest/cities/tables/SUB-EST2009-05-36.xls |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-03-27 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429224122/http://www.census.gov/popest/cities/tables/SUB-EST2009-05-36.xls |archivedate=2011-04-29 |df= }}</ref> only one fatality was reported. A tree fell on a Pennsylvania couple's vehicle and killed the wife.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20100918/ap_on_re_us/us_nyc_storm;_ylt=AsD_z4dvHjZAPjM4tz1rFRas0NUE;_ylu=X3oDMTNnYXRhODhzBGFzc2V0A2FwLzIwMTAwOTE4L3VzX255Y19zdG9ybQRjY29kZQNtb3N0cG9wdWxhcgRjcG9zAzYEcG9zAzMEcHQDaG9tZV9jb2tlBHNlYwN5bl9oZWFkbGluZV9saXN0BHNsawNhdXRob3JpdGllczI- Authorities: 2 tornadoes struck NYC during storm], Yahoo! News, Retrieved 18 September 2010.</ref> * On September 22, 2010, in the [[Hegewisch, Chicago|Hegewisch]] neighborhood of [[Chicago]], a wet microburst hit with winds upwards of {{convert|100|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}}, causing severe localized damage and power outages, including fallen-tree impacts into at least four homes. No fatalities were reported.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagobreakingnews.com/2010/09/storm-front-leaves-damage-in-its-wake.html|title=Breaking News - Chicago Tribune|website=www.chicagobreakingnews.com}}</ref> * On May 27, 2011, in the [[Morgantown, West Virginia]] neighborhood of [[Westover, West Virginia|Westover]], a wet microburst hit with winds in the {{convert|70|-|80|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} range. The [[National Weather Service]], reported that "numerous trees came down in the Westover area. A metal roof from a car dealership was blown off in downtown Morgantown...while trees were uprooted on the campus of [[West Virginia University]], including a 122-year-old [[silver maple]] which was the fifth oldest tree on the campus. The strong winds knocked down or uprooted trees sporadically eastward until the storm reached the Pleasant Hill Cemetery."<ref>http://wboy.com/blog.cfm?func=view&entryID=4896</ref><ref>http://www.thedaonline.com/news/stewart-hall-s-122-year-old-silver-maple-toppled-during-storm-1.2355659</ref> * On June 14, 2011 a microburst hit [[Norman, Oklahoma]] (a suburb of [[Oklahoma City]]) with windspeeds of up to {{convert|82|mi/h|km/h}} and hail up to golf ball size. An inch (2.54&nbsp;cm) of rain fell within 20 minutes, causing areas of [[flash flood]]ing. The storm caused widespread damage to both residences and businesses across the town. Electrical poles were snapped causing power outages to 33,000 residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/oun/?n=events-20110614|title=Norman, OK|first=US Department of Commerce, NOAA, National Weather|last=Service|website=www.srh.noaa.gov}}</ref> * On July 31, 2011, a microburst hit in the [[Victorville, California]] thousands were customers had lost power. * On July 18, 2012, a microburst hit in [[Arlington, Massachusetts]]. Gusts were 70 to 80&nbsp;mph, with worst damage in about a square mile area. Many trees and utility poles were damaged, tearing power lines from homes. There was one report of a fish blown five blocks from a pond that was near the center of the storm.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Parker |first1=Brock |title=Trees damaged by winds in Arlington |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2012/07/19/microburst-storm-hit-arlington-hard/tCR4QfGvptm7azIIZbguwO/story.html |publisher=The Boston Globe |accessdate=30 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Scalese |first1=Roberto |title=PHOTOS: Microburst Hammers Arlington |url=https://patch.com/massachusetts/arlington/microburst-hammers-arlington |website=Arlington Patch |publisher=Patch Media |accessdate=30 June 2018}}</ref> * On August 30, 2012, a severe microburst hit in [[Moreno Valley, California]], and winds gust to 90&nbsp;mph squall line in [[Apple Valley, California]]. * On July 19, 2013, a microburst hit in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] causing severely knocked out trees and power lines. Wind gusts have been reported to reach 70-80&nbsp;mph.{{Citation needed|date={{currentmonthname}} {{currentyear}}}} * On July 3, 2014, in the town of [[Cherryville, North Carolina]] a wet microburst tore apart a portion of a gas station car wash and brought down powerlines and trees. One tree fell on top of a mobile home nearly cutting it in half. The resident was injured when the fallen tree pinned him to the floor.<ref>[http://centralnc.twcnews.com/content/news/charlotte/709441/portion-of-cherryville-hit-hard-by-strong-storms/ Portion of Cherryville Hit Hard by Strong Storms], Time warner Cable News, Retrieved July 6, 2014.</ref> * On July 7, 2014, a microburst hit [[Tomball, Texas]] causing severe localized damage and power outages, including fallen-trees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.click2houston.com/news/microburst-does-major-damage-in-tomball/26839520|title=Microburst does major damage in Tomball|first=Mary|last=Cuervo|date=8 July 2014|publisher=}}</ref> * On July 26, 2014, a wet microburst hit northern parts of [[Phoenix, Arizona]] felling trees, damaging homes, and causing power outages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/phoenix/2014/07/27/metro-phoenix-storms/13238085/|title=Storm damage, outages around metro Phoenix|publisher=}}</ref> * On August 7, 2014 an apparent microburst toppled dozens of boats in the [[Dillon Reservoir]] in [[Dillon, Colorado]], leaving emergency workers scrambling to get boaters out of the cold water.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/local-news/dozens-of-boaters-thrown-into-dillon-reservoir-due-to-apparent-microburst08072014|title=Dozens of boaters thrown into Dillon Reservoir by apparent microburst|first=TheDenverChannel.com Team , Marshall|last=Zelinger|date=8 August 2014|publisher=}}</ref> * On June 23, 2015, a microburst hit Gloucester County and Camden County, New Jersey, causing major power outages across the region. Many homes and roads were damaged by fallen trees and debris from the storm.{{Citation needed|date={{currentmonthname}} {{currentyear}}}} * On July 29, 2015, a microburst hit in the [[Phelan, California]] had knocked out power.{{Citation needed|date={{currentmonthname}} {{currentyear}}}} * On May 4, 2017, a microburst hit in [[Lacey, Washington]] had uprooted trees and fallen power lines. * On Sept 3, 2017, a microburst hit in [[Santa Barbara, California]] and knocked off numerous trees and many landed on cars with many power lines down. Multiple traffic accidents occurred and 56 people were tossed into the water. A 22-foot sailboat was also overturned and was sinking into the ocean.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.keyt.com/news/santa-barbara-s-county/massivie-storm-system-quickly-rolls-through-santa-barbara/616144265|title=Massive storm system quickly rolls through Santa Barbara}}</ref>
